    "text": "3.1.1 Coarse-grained Vulnerable Method Localization. Directly feeding raw fix commit diffs to the LLM often leads to hallucinations because the model may struggle to distinguish the actual remediation logic from irrelevant code churn. To mitigate this issue, this submodule serves as a pre-filter to identify methods strictly relevant to the vulnerability and thereby reduces the search space for the subsequent fine-grained analysis. However, effectively filtering these methods presents a challenge as developers frequently interleave security patches with non-security maintenance such as refactoring, formatting, or feature updates. To address this, we introduce Method Change Type (MCT) as a semantic abstraction mechanism. Unlike raw line-level diffs, MCT categorizes how a method is modified, establishing a correlation between the nature of the repair and the vulnerability type. For instance, fixing a Missing Input Validation vulnerability typically involves adding conditional checks, whereas remediating an Information Exposure vulnerability involves deletions. By explicitly defining these patterns, we guide the LLM to focus on methods whose modification signatures align with the expected repair strategy for the specific vulnerability. Formally, we guide the LLM in localizing potentially vulnerable methods by a vulnerability knowledge tuple 𝐾 vul = ( MCT , CVE , CWE ) , which is composed as follows: • MCT (Method Change Type). MCT provides a high-level classification of modified methods in patches, facilitating the LLM’s focus on vulnerable methods during Coarse-grained Vulnerable Method Localization. We define the following sets of methods. 𝑀 𝑝𝑟𝑒 : The set of all methods in the pre-fix version of files modified by the commit. 𝑀 𝑝𝑜𝑠𝑡 : The set of all methods in the",
